  "summary": "Open interest in futures markets is the total number of contracts that are currently open. Each contract consists of a buyer (long position) and a seller (short position). The level of open interest changes based on the traders involved in a transaction. The scenario presented is one where both the buyer and the seller are closing out pre-existing positions. A trader buying to close a position must have previously been short. A trader selling to close a position must have previously been long. When these two traders transact, the buyer's purchase cancels their short position, and the seller's sale cancels their long position. As a result, one long position and one short position are simultaneously eliminated from the market. This removes one complete contract from the total pool of outstanding contracts. Consequently, the total open interest decreases by one. The statement that open interest increases by one is incorrect. An increase in open interest only occurs when both the buyer and the seller are opening new positions, thereby creating a new contract.",
  "conclusion": "The statement that open interest increases by one when both sides of a transaction are closing out existing positions is false. In reality, open interest decreases by one."
